<br>
Think I'm on the same wavelength as Brut on this topic; unless it's very poorly implemented, making shields avoid (block) and/or somewhat effectively (non-ac based) mitigate damage just adds potential options to encounters.  It also might help break up the cookie-cutter MT warrior setup rut we are in now, not a bad thing IMHO.<br>
<br>
Having said this, I do see/agree with Furor's point with respect to the DPS disparity between melee classes, I just don't know that increasing warrior DPS is all that good a solution for the game.  <br>
<br>
At one level, it would just raise the bar for average mob HP needed to make an encounter &quot;non-trivial&quot;, setting the stage for Yet Even Longer fights.  I always thought that the fights in Kunark were a bit too short (30 min of setup for 30 seconds of fighting, tho VERY intense), but also feel some of the luclin ones are WAY to long now (10 min of setup *yay AEbuffs!* for 30 min of fight).  Seemed to me that Velious had the balance about right, 5-10 minutes or so.<br>
<br>
Anyway, so how do you fix the high end DPS disparity with melee?  I can see a number of options, none of them all that great.  Kind of boils down to a fundamental design decision about how they &quot;want&quot; big melee-centric fights to work methinks:<br>
<br>
a). allow a properly equipped MT to (barely) hold mob aggro with DPS melee classes (monk rog) doing their max damage output.<br>
<br>
-or-<br>
<br>
b). require DPS melee classes (monk rog) to substantially throttle back on DPS to avoid stealing aggro.<br>
<br>
Right now, most fights seem to be basically option &quot;A&quot;.  Adding MORE DPS to a MT will only INCREASE the amount of DPS other classes can do w/o stealing aggro... not really what's needed/wanted/appropriate imho.  Chosing option &quot;B&quot; at this point would require serious futzing with aggro code, FD, and evade- but if done right, could reduce the *effective* DPS of those classes back to where they should be; about 20-30pct more than a dual wielding warrior attacking from behind a mob.  <br>
<br>
Problem is, many of the ways to do that (reducing effectiveness of taunt, reducing MT DPS, etc.) also serve to make knight classes much better potential MTs than warriors... not an easy issue.  Has always bugged me that a mob would rather kill a cleric who's healing the person it's hitting, more than the toon behind it that's stabbing it's kidneys out in 600hp chunks...<br>
<br>
Finally, making shields avoid damage rather than mitigate it seems like a pretty good design decision actually... it still allows the &quot;oshit&quot; factor of a max damage round or delayed heal taking out a MT, which means more than one warrior per raid needed.  Higher mitigation would do the opposite (which was a big part of the problem with defensive...)<br>
<br>
Phew.  Longer post than I planned, sorry!<br>
<br>
RdT. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaveenlucenthawk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aveen Lucenthawk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/22/02 1:32:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1109.topic&index=152>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_ale.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: new on test</span><hr size=1> Absor,<br>
